+\subsection{Phase 2b: Stage-conditioned annealing (\texttt{adaptive\_tanh\_stage})}
+\label{sec:planned-stage}
+
+The StackCube inversion (F9/F10) reveals that within-episode time-based annealing
+(\texttt{adaptive\_tanh\_episode}) fails on hierarchical tasks because it schedules
+$k$ as a function of \emph{time}, not \emph{task progress}. We propose
+\texttt{adaptive\_tanh\_stage}: the same $k$ schedule but reset at each stage
+transition. Formally, let $t_{\text{stage}}$ be the number of steps since the current
+stage began and $T$ be \texttt{max\_episode\_steps}:
+\begin{equation}
+    k(t_{\text{stage}}) = k_{\min} + (k_{\max} - k_{\min}) \cdot \frac{t_{\text{stage}}}{T}
+\end{equation}
+When \texttt{is\_cubeA\_grasped} flips (stage transition), $t_{\text{stage}}$ resets
+to~0 for that environment, restarting the wide-to-narrow curriculum.
+
+On single-stage tasks (PickCube, PushCube, LiftPegUpright), $t_{\text{stage}} =
+t_{\text{elapsed}}$, so behavior is identical to \texttt{adaptive\_tanh\_episode}.
+On StackCube, stage~2 (placement) begins at $k{=}2$ (wide), giving the policy a full
+exploration budget for the placement sub-goal.
+
+\textbf{Success criterion:} StackCube mean $> 0.85$ across seeds $\{1, 42, 123\}$
+with no regression on PickCube vs.\ \texttt{adaptive\_tanh\_episode} ($0.979$).
